\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that criteria 1\'2C 3\'2C 4\'2C and 7 do not comply with minimum standards while the remainder are all in need of improvement. \line The evaluator stated that the proposed programme is poorly designed. Some of the major shortcomings include\'3A  \line 1. The total credit value of the proposed programme is actually 421 credits and not 424 credits as indicated in the submission. The total credit value of proposed programme exceeds the minimum requirement of 360 credits with more than 61 credits.\line 2. The proposed programme does not have the support of the Tourism industry and no Tourism association has given it the support to make it credible. Given that many skills audits and studies have been done in the Tourism industry in South Africa\'2C this proposed programme bears no linkage to any of those studies done.\line 3. All the modules at third year are on NQF level 7\'2C which implies that the programme does not meet the requirements of the HEQF. \line 4. The proposed programme has very little content that focuses on the discipline of Tourism. \line 5. BCC\'E2\'80\'99s policies contain no direct reference as how distance learning will be facilitated\'2C although the submission does make some reference to distance learning \'28using technology\'29 and contact learning. Since the proposed programme will be offered as a distance learning programme\'2C not much is said about how distance learning students will be assessed\'2C and where they will be assessed to ensure the validity and reliability of assessment practices. \line 6. Admission requirements are not in line with requirements as the proposed programme uses the Higher Certificate South African Tourism and Advanced Certificate in African and European Tourism\'2C OR modules from these programmes as a  basis for admission. \line \line The academic staff members have no formal Tourism qualifications. The experience in Tourism was based on one staff member\'2C but her experience is primarily in the retail sector \'28travel agency\'2C airlines\'2C etc\'29. Thus\'2C inasfar as the discipline of Tourism is concerned\'2C no staff member has the competence to offer the Environmental and Cultural Tourism module.\line \line In terms of Criterion 7 the evaluator noted that since this programme will be offered via distance learning\'2C the infrastructural requirements\'2C e.g. venues and computer labs may not necessarily be a requirement. According to the submission some students may come in to use the computer facilities to view DVDs\'2C or other teaching aids. Unfortunately\'2C it is not known what percentage of the students will make use of their facilities. It would be unreasonable to expect such students to travel to Gauteng to access distance learning opportunities and it can then be argued as to whether this programme will still be distance learning. A major concern is also the lack of library resources. The BCC library only has two Tourism books\line \line The Directorate concurs that the programme cannot be accredited. \line \line \cell \pard 

